WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.353 --> 00:00:11.020
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.020 --> 00:00:12.300
LANG LANG: Good morning.

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:14.130
Thanks for being here.

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:16.180
I'm very happy to be here
for the second time.

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:19.540
But the first time I wasn't
on this stage.

00:00:19.540 --> 00:00:21.355
I was just visiting
the office.

00:00:21.355 --> 00:00:24.890
It's a very cool office,
I must say.

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:32.159
And so I prepared some morning
songs for you to wake up.

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.480
So a few Chopin pieces.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:40.560
I will start with one of the
very beautiful nocturnes and

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:46.060
then one or two etudes, and
then a Chopin waltz.

00:00:46.060 --> 00:00:51.340
So hopefully, we will get really
waked after 20 minutes

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:52.200
of performance.

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:53.999
Thank you.

00:00:53.999 --> 00:00:55.496
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:59.987 --> 00:16:42.170
[PIANO MUSIC - CHOPIN]

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:52.272
[APPLAUSE]

00:16:52.272 --> 00:16:55.740
JEFF SPURGEON: Hello, I'm Jeff
Spurgeon from WQXR, New York's

00:16:55.740 --> 00:17:00.750
classical station, 105.9
FM, online at wqxr.org.

00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:03.550
You may not know, because
nobody told you,

00:17:03.550 --> 00:17:05.970
this is Lang Lang.

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:11.144
He's a classical pianist,
reasonably well known

00:17:11.144 --> 00:17:13.339
all over the globe.

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:18.290
And it's quite a wonderful
thing to hear you play.

00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:21.619
Let me ask you, what was
your warm-up for

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:22.664
this just this morning?

00:17:22.664 --> 00:17:23.839
Did you warm up this morning?

00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:24.970
When's the last time you
touched a piano?

00:17:24.970 --> 00:17:27.910
LANG LANG: I didn't warm up.

00:17:27.910 --> 00:17:29.275
I woke up around 10:20.

00:17:29.275 --> 00:17:33.274
I'm like, oh, god.

00:17:33.274 --> 00:17:38.590
And we were running like crazy
down the street to get here.

00:17:38.590 --> 00:17:41.730
And I'm really grateful
that you are here

00:17:41.730 --> 00:17:43.270
today waiting for me.

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:44.912
And thank you very much.

00:17:44.912 --> 00:17:46.328
JEFF SPURGEON: It's
really wonderful.

00:17:46.328 --> 00:17:49.640
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:52.310
JEFF SPURGEON: It's
extraordinary to have all that

00:17:52.310 --> 00:17:54.410
music just in your hands,
just at your command.

00:17:54.410 --> 00:17:56.080
But that's what you do.

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:57.810
LANG LANG: By the way,
Rubinstein said-- one of the

00:17:57.810 --> 00:17:58.800
greatest pianists.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:03.850
And he said he has 60 piano
concertos in his head.

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:09.390
And basically during his
70s or 80s he said

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:10.780
just call me up.

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:12.450
Wake me up in the middle
of the night-- like,

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:14.630
let's say, 4:00 AM--

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:19.570
and I can play whatever piece
you want, in concert level.

00:18:19.570 --> 00:18:21.710
JEFF SPURGEON: Well,
I believe it.

00:18:21.710 --> 00:18:22.840
But so can you.

00:18:22.840 --> 00:18:25.100
But so can you.

00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:27.590
He had a little more practice
over time than you so far.

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:29.080
But you'll be there.

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:33.740
In China, Lang Lang is credited
with influencing some

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:38.590
40 million kids to take
up classical piano.

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:40.370
Now, I know that 40 million
is not maybe a

00:18:40.370 --> 00:18:42.070
huge number at Google.

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:47.030
But still, it's a reasonably
large number of people to

00:18:47.030 --> 00:18:48.190
persuade to take up.

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:50.100
And when you think about all
the pianos that have to be

00:18:50.100 --> 00:18:53.170
made, and all the music that has
to be printed, and all the

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:55.600
lessons that have to be paid
for, I would say that you are,

00:18:55.600 --> 00:18:59.570
without question, classical
music's greatest job creator.

00:18:59.570 --> 00:18:59.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:59.930 --> 00:19:02.450
JEFF SPURGEON: I don't think
there's anybody who's going to

00:19:02.450 --> 00:19:04.450
do more than that
than you are.

00:19:04.450 --> 00:19:07.030
Lang Lang's new album on the
Sony label is "The Chopin

00:19:07.030 --> 00:19:12.462
Album." It contains, at its
heart, the Opus 25 set of a

00:19:12.462 --> 00:19:16.150
dozen etudes, studies for piano,
that you have been

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:17.240
studying since I think
you were what?

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:18.720
Eight is when you started
to play those things?

00:19:18.720 --> 00:19:20.400
LANG LANG: Yeah, I started
to play the Chopin

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:23.780
Etudes when I was eight.

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:24.390
JEFF SPURGEON: Took them
on the road when

00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:25.430
you were 12 or 13?

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:29.100
LANG LANG: Yeah, I played the
complete etudes when I was 13.

00:19:29.100 --> 00:19:30.292
JEFF SPURGEON: Right.

00:19:30.292 --> 00:19:35.750
LANG LANG: And it was very
tiring to play those pieces.

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:39.235
I mean, it drives me nuts and
drives my neighbors nuts.

00:19:39.235 --> 00:19:39.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:42.680
LANG LANG: I really feel
bad about it, you know.

00:19:42.680 --> 00:19:46.300
Recently, I started practicing
at my apartment here and

00:19:46.300 --> 00:19:49.910
started practicing the
Chopin etudes.

00:19:49.910 --> 00:19:51.190
And then my neighbor
knocked at my door.

00:19:51.190 --> 00:19:52.810
And he said could you stop?

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:53.200
Could you stop?

00:19:53.200 --> 00:19:53.510
JEFF SPURGEON: Really?

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:54.180
Did they really?

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:55.620
You're making that up.

00:19:55.620 --> 00:19:56.230
LANG LANG: No, no.

00:19:56.230 --> 00:19:58.810
I mean, there's a one neighbor
who knows who I am, so she's

00:19:58.810 --> 00:20:03.020
always like, oh, that's
really wonderful.

00:20:03.020 --> 00:20:07.000
But then another neighbor, I
think, living downstairs--

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:10.090
because I always like to
practice after 11:00 to find

00:20:10.090 --> 00:20:10.810
inspiration.

00:20:10.810 --> 00:20:13.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:14.900
LANG LANG: And this
lady, I think she

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:16.295
hate me all the time.

00:20:19.350 --> 00:20:20.560
JEFF SPURGEON: So you've been
playing these since you were

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:24.100
eight, playing them in public
since you were 13.

00:20:24.100 --> 00:20:26.040
Why record them now?

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:27.310
Why not a little earlier?

00:20:27.310 --> 00:20:28.600
Why not wait a couple
more years?

00:20:28.600 --> 00:20:31.150
Maybe the wine will mellow a
little more in the bottle.

00:20:31.150 --> 00:20:33.820
Why decide to do these now?

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:38.610
LANG LANG: Ever since I'm 30,
I like to do some more

00:20:38.610 --> 00:20:42.610
repertoire which I played a lot
when I was a kid and also

00:20:42.610 --> 00:20:44.820
putting in some new pieces.

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:47.970
I actually thought to
do the 24 etudes to

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:50.930
complete the cycle.

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:56.240
But actually, I thought maybe
I should do something, not

00:20:56.240 --> 00:20:59.890
just technical pieces, but
also very artistic pieces

00:20:59.890 --> 00:21:04.120
combined for the Chopin
first solo for me to

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:09.170
record and also to hear.

00:21:09.170 --> 00:21:12.640
I was actually watching the
video that I did when I was

00:21:12.640 --> 00:21:17.620
13, playing the complete
etudes.

00:21:17.620 --> 00:21:19.310
And I find a few wrong notes.

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:20.660
I'm like, yeah.

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:25.530
But I'm now playing a few of
those pieces, like the "Winter

00:21:25.530 --> 00:21:27.940
Wind" and the "Ocean" etudes.

00:21:27.940 --> 00:21:30.280
Now it feels slightly easier--

00:21:30.280 --> 00:21:31.410
slightly.

00:21:31.410 --> 00:21:34.540
So that seems like
a good sign.

00:21:34.540 --> 00:21:42.000
After 17 years of practice, my
technique is going somewhere.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.170
But more importantly, it's
the musical sense.

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:50.270
There are so many new things
I'm trying to interpret in

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:53.350
this album to try to find
different colors, like you

00:21:53.350 --> 00:21:58.420
have here, different levels of
colors and the combination of

00:21:58.420 --> 00:22:03.500
the styling of Chopin, and the
romantic period of repertoire.

00:22:03.500 --> 00:22:06.510
And especially last
year, I did Liszt.

00:22:06.510 --> 00:22:10.130
So I thought this was a nice
momentum to do Chopin.

00:22:10.130 --> 00:22:12.230
So next year will be
very different.

00:22:12.230 --> 00:22:13.130
JEFF SPURGEON: What's
next year?

00:22:13.130 --> 00:22:15.350
LANG LANG: Next year I will
do Prokofiev and Bartok.

00:22:15.350 --> 00:22:15.690
JEFF SPURGEON: Wow.

00:22:15.690 --> 00:22:16.440
OK.

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:17.840
LANG LANG: So it's very,
very different--

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:18.260
JEFF SPURGEON: Gnarly.

00:22:18.260 --> 00:22:18.802
LANG LANG: --approach.

00:22:18.802 --> 00:22:19.900
JEFF SPURGEON: Yeah,
totally different.

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:21.120
A totally different world.

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:23.120
There's some unusual pieces
on this album.

00:22:23.120 --> 00:22:25.400
The "Andante spianato" and
"Grande polonaise." big

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:28.100
favorite of yours, done with
orchestra sometimes, but

00:22:28.100 --> 00:22:29.780
there's the solo version.

00:22:29.780 --> 00:22:32.120
You've always liked
this piece?

00:22:32.120 --> 00:22:32.660
LANG LANG: Not really.

00:22:32.660 --> 00:22:35.800
I mean, when I was a
kid, I hated it.

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:42.420
Because no matter how great the
works are, if there are so

00:22:42.420 --> 00:22:45.670
many pianists playing the same
piece not at a very good

00:22:45.670 --> 00:22:48.430
level, then you will
feel kind of bored.

00:22:48.430 --> 00:22:52.912
And so that exactly happened
when I was a kid.

00:22:52.912 --> 00:22:55.330
I heard so many interpretations
of this piece

00:22:55.330 --> 00:22:58.090
that I got totally
overwhelmed.

00:22:58.090 --> 00:22:59.900
And I didn't like it.

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:02.430
Then I came to America.

00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:05.865
And I studied at Curtis
in Philadelphia.

00:23:05.865 --> 00:23:07.180
Do you know the Philly
cheese steak?

00:23:07.180 --> 00:23:08.430
It's pretty good.

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:19.890
Anyway, in Philadelphia, a boy
from Kiev, he also studied

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:21.540
with the same teacher as
me, Gary Graffman.

00:23:21.540 --> 00:23:22.240
JEFF SPURGEON: Gary Graffman.

00:23:22.240 --> 00:23:24.530
LANG LANG: And he played
in the student recital.

00:23:24.530 --> 00:23:26.450
I was shocked by his playing.

00:23:26.450 --> 00:23:30.180
I'm like, wow, this piece
is spectacular.

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:32.710
And then I started to
loving this piece.

00:23:32.710 --> 00:23:33.940
Thanks to him, of course.

00:23:33.940 --> 00:23:39.350
And so sometimes one amazing
performance really changes

00:23:39.350 --> 00:23:41.780
your entire view of a work.

00:23:41.780 --> 00:23:45.420
And that's what happened in
the "Spianato" and "Grande

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:47.400
polonaise."

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:48.250
JEFF SPURGEON: Nocturnes.

00:23:48.250 --> 00:23:50.250
You played, actually, a
wonderful cross-section of the

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:52.640
album just a few minutes ago.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:53.650
There's a piece on this album.

00:23:53.650 --> 00:23:54.630
It's the last selection.

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:57.630
It's called "Tristesse." And it
features a singer named Oh

00:23:57.630 --> 00:24:00.610
Land who is from--

00:24:00.610 --> 00:24:01.180
LANG LANG: Sweden, I think.

00:24:01.180 --> 00:24:02.570
JEFF SPURGEON: Sweden.

00:24:02.570 --> 00:24:05.810
She lives in Williamsburg,
because most people do.

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:07.950
LANG LANG: Yeah, Brooklyn's
getting big.

00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:09.010
JEFF SPURGEON: It's beautiful.

00:24:09.010 --> 00:24:10.360
And can you tell me
the story of this?

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:12.380
Because it's from a
film, "Tristesse."

00:24:12.380 --> 00:24:13.170
LANG LANG: Right.

00:24:13.170 --> 00:24:16.790
We did a film during the Chopin
year called "The Flying

00:24:16.790 --> 00:24:22.540
Machine." So it's basically
adapted to a novel about

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:24.570
Poland today.

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:28.310
And it's compared to
Chopin's days.

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:35.290
So actually, I was an
actor in this movie.

00:24:35.290 --> 00:24:38.945
And my partner was Heather
Graham from "Austin

00:24:38.945 --> 00:24:41.610
Powers," the girl.

00:24:41.610 --> 00:24:42.590
JEFF SPURGEON: Yeah,
Heather Graham.

00:24:42.590 --> 00:24:45.560
Many, many faces lit up when
you said those words.

00:24:48.650 --> 00:24:50.400
LANG LANG: But that one
was pretty classic.

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:53.452
I need a hungover thing.

00:24:53.452 --> 00:24:55.600
I miss the baby, yeah.

00:24:55.600 --> 00:25:01.560
And so that film, actually, was
quite inspiring, because

00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:03.900
it was Chopin's music,
and takes the

00:25:03.900 --> 00:25:05.950
journey of a piano, actually.

00:25:05.950 --> 00:25:07.990
The piano became a
flying machine.

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:11.680
So we take the kids
over the world.

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:15.140
And so the theme song, we
actually thought the

00:25:15.140 --> 00:25:18.470
"Tristesse," which is Opus 10,
Number 3, etudes, is such a

00:25:18.470 --> 00:25:23.060
beautiful melody, which I played
second to the last.

00:25:23.060 --> 00:25:27.890
And so we transcribed that to
the theme song, so we got this

00:25:27.890 --> 00:25:29.900
beautiful voice.

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:33.070
Her name is pretty
fun, Oh Land.

00:25:33.070 --> 00:25:37.760
So in the beginning, I didn't
know if it's a he or a she.

00:25:37.760 --> 00:25:43.170
Then when I heard the voice, I
most certainly said, it's she.

00:25:43.170 --> 00:25:45.970
And she did a wonderful job.

00:25:45.970 --> 00:25:46.910
JEFF SPURGEON: It's
a sweet song.

00:25:46.910 --> 00:25:50.360
And a lot of popular
songs have been

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:51.460
written on Chopin themes.

00:25:51.460 --> 00:25:52.380
LANG LANG: Yes.

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:55.310
JEFF SPURGEON: And this is
another one, which is great.

00:25:55.310 --> 00:25:58.130
Your foundation, let's talk
about that because that's such

00:25:58.130 --> 00:25:58.510
a big deal.

00:25:58.510 --> 00:26:01.540
The Lang Lang International
Music Foundation, it's going

00:26:01.540 --> 00:26:02.160
great guns.

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:04.430
You had some kids, I think, from
part of that program on

00:26:04.430 --> 00:26:06.170
"The Tonight Show" recently?

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:08.600
LANG LANG: Yeah, two weeks
ago, I was on Jay Leno.

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:10.980
JEFF SPURGEON: Four minutes of
classical music on network

00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:11.600
television.

00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:12.636
It was extraordinary.

00:26:12.636 --> 00:26:14.620
It was four whole minutes.

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:16.850
It was amazing.

00:26:16.850 --> 00:26:18.050
LANG LANG: These days,
it's hard to get

00:26:18.050 --> 00:26:19.080
classical music on--

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:21.465
JEFF SPURGEON: That's
exactly right.

00:26:21.465 --> 00:26:23.460
LANG LANG: Anyway, I mean,
Jay is a good friend.

00:26:23.460 --> 00:26:28.690
And I mean, his name is Jay
Jay now, you know, after--

00:26:28.690 --> 00:26:28.890
JEFF SPURGEON: After
Lang Lang.

00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:32.310
Right, sure.

00:26:32.310 --> 00:26:34.020
LANG LANG: Oh, my god,
he has 400 cars.

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:36.120
Anyway, let's not
talk about that.

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:44.360
So we actually had a very
fortunate selection of

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:49.400
wonderful tenants from
the Los Angeles area.

00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:52.120
I mean, some of the kids,
actually, I know them before,

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:55.060
because they performed with me,
my foundation, actually.

00:26:55.060 --> 00:26:55.960
JEFF SPURGEON: They were
young kids, too.

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:56.980
There were 10 of them.

00:26:56.980 --> 00:26:57.950
So Lang Lang played.

00:26:57.950 --> 00:27:02.170
You play some "La companella,"
and the E-flat waltz that you

00:27:02.170 --> 00:27:03.280
heard part of here.

00:27:03.280 --> 00:27:07.110
And then 10 kids, five other
Steinways around in the room,

00:27:07.110 --> 00:27:09.405
and they all joined you for the
Mozart "Ronda alla Turca."

00:27:09.405 --> 00:27:11.740
LANG LANG: Yeah, Turkish
March [HUMS TUNE].

00:27:11.740 --> 00:27:13.060
I'm sure you know it.

00:27:13.060 --> 00:27:16.670
And it was so beautiful
that I really enjoyed

00:27:16.670 --> 00:27:17.860
working with them.

00:27:17.860 --> 00:27:20.160
But the way they played,
it was magnificent.

00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:21.390
JEFF SPURGEON: Yeah,
very sweet.

00:27:21.390 --> 00:27:26.410
LANG LANG: And I mean, I thought
everyone watching our

00:27:26.410 --> 00:27:29.640
next generation perform,
it's a special moment.

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:32.210
And for me, it's
very inspiring.

00:27:32.210 --> 00:27:36.990
And that's what our foundation
is wanting to do, to work with

00:27:36.990 --> 00:27:41.330
the next generation of artists,
and helping them to

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:44.780
support them to achieve their
dreams, just like many of the

00:27:44.780 --> 00:27:47.480
mentor helped me when
I was very young.

00:27:47.480 --> 00:27:49.950
JEFF SPURGEON: So it's about
helping the next generation,

00:27:49.950 --> 00:27:52.000
not necessarily about
classical music.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:53.700
I mean, it is classical
focused, I think.

00:27:53.700 --> 00:27:57.110
LANG LANG: Yeah, it will be a
focus on classical and piano.

00:27:57.110 --> 00:28:04.360
But at the same time, we will
also do some event, let's say,

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:10.690
with the Grammy people
and VHI people.

00:28:10.690 --> 00:28:16.930
So we are trying to break the
boundaries through this

