00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:48.300
they were actually playing
something.

00:40:48.300 --> 00:40:52.190
And we can actually play
together, like, two pianos or

00:40:52.190 --> 00:40:53.010
three pianos.

00:40:53.010 --> 00:40:56.200
Or violin, play a trio,
a little trio.

00:40:56.200 --> 00:40:59.070
And music's like language.

00:40:59.070 --> 00:41:00.420
We need a communication.

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:01.900
We need to use our language.

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:05.250
You know, if you learn a new
language, if you don't use it,

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:08.490
you're not interested, and
you forget about it.

00:41:08.490 --> 00:41:13.450
So communication is
very important.

00:41:13.450 --> 00:41:17.200
JEFF SPURGEON: I know there's
at least one more question.

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:20.160
AUDIENCE: I think I could
just ask here.

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:20.880
JEFF SPURGEON: I'll repeat it.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:22.560
AUDIENCE: First of all, as a
Chinese, I am very proud of

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:24.330
your-- you know, everything.

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:25.331
LANG LANG: Thank you.

00:41:25.331 --> 00:41:28.488
AUDIENCE: Like [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:28.488 --> 00:41:30.090
Really good job.

00:41:30.090 --> 00:41:35.770
My question is do you have any
plan to do some record like

00:41:35.770 --> 00:41:38.540
Bach or something more classic
like "Goldberg--"

00:41:38.540 --> 00:41:39.400
LANG LANG: "Goldberg
Variation."

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:41.760
AUDIENCE: Yeah, like
like that.

00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:44.360
JEFF SPURGEON: OK, so the
question was what are your

00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:45.760
plans for your next
recordings?

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:48.720
And will you do Bach,
specifically?

00:41:48.720 --> 00:41:50.130
LANG LANG: I mean,
I love Bach.

00:41:50.130 --> 00:41:54.260
When I was a kid, I played
Bach's work every week.

00:41:54.260 --> 00:41:56.753
And I tried to memorize
a work by Bach every

00:41:56.753 --> 00:41:59.102
week to train my brain.

00:41:59.102 --> 00:42:02.360
By the way, after that, you can
remember every cellphone

00:42:02.360 --> 00:42:03.610
number you want.

00:42:06.330 --> 00:42:12.540
And Bach is really, really
challenging, but incredible.

00:42:12.540 --> 00:42:14.970
Certainly, I would love to
record the "Goldberg

00:42:14.970 --> 00:42:18.060
Variation." Certainly,
I will do more

00:42:18.060 --> 00:42:21.100
classic repertoire records.

00:42:21.100 --> 00:42:23.960
But it needs to be balanced.

00:42:23.960 --> 00:42:26.790
So this year and last year
I did all the romantics.

00:42:26.790 --> 00:42:28.770
And then next year, it
will be contemporary.

00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:29.360
And then, you know.

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:35.050
So I'm trying to balance
the recordings.

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:36.771
Thanks for bringing the
"Goldberg," by the way.

00:42:39.930 --> 00:42:42.150
AUDIENCE: So there's a
lot of talk about--

00:42:42.150 --> 00:42:43.880
sorry, I'm very tall.

00:42:43.880 --> 00:42:46.530
There's a lot of talk
about bringing

00:42:46.530 --> 00:42:47.620
classical music to children.

00:42:47.620 --> 00:42:49.905
And I am, in some sense,
a product of that.

00:42:49.905 --> 00:42:52.850
My father went way out of his
way to play classical music.

00:42:52.850 --> 00:42:54.040
He really enjoyed it.

00:42:54.040 --> 00:42:56.720
And I hated it as a kid.

00:42:56.720 --> 00:42:57.460
And I'm here.

00:42:57.460 --> 00:42:59.350
So that's obviously no
longer the case.

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:06.356
But I studied, or at least I was
taught, classical guitar.

00:43:06.356 --> 00:43:10.610
And that lapsed for several
years while I went to

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:11.300
university.

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:13.650
And now I'm here, so I guess
the lapse was a little

00:43:13.650 --> 00:43:14.275
worthwhile.

00:43:14.275 --> 00:43:18.550
But what advice would you give
towards adults who have a

00:43:18.550 --> 00:43:24.040
musical sensibility, who have
musical appreciation and, I

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:27.110
guess in my case, have or, in
more general cases, do not

00:43:27.110 --> 00:43:29.260
have some degree of
musical training?

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:33.300
Because children are taught at
a very early age to begin to

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:37.560
play classical music or
any music in general.

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:40.230
Is there any fear that I should
have in terms of lack

00:43:40.230 --> 00:43:43.750
of dexterity, I guess,
plasticity of mind?

00:43:43.750 --> 00:43:46.680
What advice would you give
towards adults who want to

00:43:46.680 --> 00:43:51.970
begin to hopefully, with a lag,
reach the kind of level

00:43:51.970 --> 00:43:54.590
you operate on?

00:43:54.590 --> 00:43:56.960
LANG LANG: You are
getting deep.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:43:57.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:57.600 --> 00:43:58.850
LANG LANG: Wow.

00:44:01.030 --> 00:44:02.350
Adult.

00:44:02.350 --> 00:44:06.770
I mean, there's an app called
Magic Piano, which I

00:44:06.770 --> 00:44:08.020
co-produced.

00:44:09.530 --> 00:44:13.710
If you feel difficult to play
the real piano, try that.

00:44:13.710 --> 00:44:17.080
It will be easier to play.

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:19.250
Because somehow it's
played by itself.

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:26.830
And you can certainly buy a
piano which has a kind of

00:44:26.830 --> 00:44:28.610
high-tech disk.

00:44:28.610 --> 00:44:33.830
And then you just push whoever's
Chopin, whoever's

00:44:33.830 --> 00:44:37.220
Tchaikovsky, whoever's
Beethoven.

00:44:37.220 --> 00:44:41.100
And then you can maybe start to
see the positions down on

00:44:41.100 --> 00:44:44.660
the piano and try
to follow it.

00:44:44.660 --> 00:44:49.960
But again, I am really welcoming
of adults actually

00:44:49.960 --> 00:44:51.700
learning an instrument.

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:54.580
And especially, you
had a musical

00:44:54.580 --> 00:44:55.510
training before, right?

00:44:55.510 --> 00:44:59.170
So for you, it will be very
easy, actually, to pick it up

00:44:59.170 --> 00:45:03.410
again, the great work
you did before.

00:45:03.410 --> 00:45:05.820
And maybe now when you do
it, you will feel more

00:45:05.820 --> 00:45:06.590
comfortable.

00:45:06.590 --> 00:45:11.090
Maybe you will like it more
than when you were a kid.

00:45:11.090 --> 00:45:14.790
And also, you know, classical
guitar is pretty cool.

00:45:14.790 --> 00:45:21.000
And I'm sure when you
play, you get some

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:22.220
new dates or something.

00:45:22.220 --> 00:45:23.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:24.940
LANG LANG: I mean, that's
very encouraging.

00:45:24.940 --> 00:45:29.850
I know some of my friends, who
are adults, study piano.

00:45:29.850 --> 00:45:31.230
I say, why are you doing it?

00:45:31.230 --> 00:45:33.620
Oh, I to impress the girls.

00:45:33.620 --> 00:45:35.410
So I know lots of
those people.

00:45:35.410 --> 00:45:41.520
So it's good encouragement.

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:42.750
JEFF SPURGEON: Choice of
instrument could be important

00:45:42.750 --> 00:45:43.870
for that, too.

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:45.330
You'll get more dates with
a guitar, probably,

00:45:45.330 --> 00:45:46.740
than with an accordion.

00:45:46.740 --> 00:45:47.690
Just a thought.

00:45:47.690 --> 00:45:50.080
LANG LANG: Guitar is very
popular these days.

00:45:50.080 --> 00:45:52.520
Probably one of the instruments
I can think of

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:55.500
more popular than piano,
it's probably guitar.

00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:57.440
I would like to learn
it, actually.

00:45:57.440 --> 00:45:59.240
Guitar, I mean.

00:45:59.240 --> 00:46:01.950
Maybe I should learn
some classical

00:46:01.950 --> 00:46:04.830
guitar skill from you.

00:46:04.830 --> 00:46:06.750
AUDIENCE: I'd love
to give you a--

00:46:06.750 --> 00:46:09.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:09.960 --> 00:46:11.670
LANG LANG: I got new
lessons from you.

00:46:11.670 --> 00:46:14.330
AUDIENCE: So the point is a
competent teacher, right?

00:46:14.330 --> 00:46:14.830
LANG LANG: Great.

00:46:14.830 --> 00:46:16.020
Thank you.

00:46:16.020 --> 00:46:17.170
JEFF SPURGEON: Yes, sir?

00:46:17.170 --> 00:46:21.180
AUDIENCE: I wanted to ask, when
you memorize a piece, is

00:46:21.180 --> 00:46:22.650
it only technical?

00:46:22.650 --> 00:46:24.990
Or do you also memorize
how you feel?

00:46:24.990 --> 00:46:28.910
Is it like, before you start
playing, do you have to get

00:46:28.910 --> 00:46:30.750
into the emotion
of that piece?

00:46:30.750 --> 00:46:34.210
Or is just the music getting
you there when you hear it?

00:46:40.930 --> 00:46:45.080
LANG LANG: First, sometimes I
hear great music in my ear.

00:46:45.080 --> 00:46:51.350
Whether it's any type of music,
I'm just trying to

00:46:51.350 --> 00:46:53.580
memorize the melodies first.

00:46:53.580 --> 00:46:59.180
And I want to somehow play
it on the piano.

00:46:59.180 --> 00:47:02.430
But some work, I know it for
many years, and it doesn't

00:47:02.430 --> 00:47:06.920
mean that you start to love
those repertoire right away.

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:10.030
Some pieces take a few
years to digest.

00:47:10.030 --> 00:47:13.250
And then you're like,
wow, I should do it.

00:47:13.250 --> 00:47:16.490
So first comes to the
general stuff.

00:47:16.490 --> 00:47:19.580
You read a score after you're
really liking this piece.

00:47:19.580 --> 00:47:20.490
You want to learn it, right?

00:47:20.490 --> 00:47:26.310
So you learn it from the score,
and you play simply,

00:47:26.310 --> 00:47:31.160
whether just play by your
right hand or putting it

00:47:31.160 --> 00:47:34.000
together, practice.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:41.140
And after that, you are trying
to analyzing the piece and

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:44.560
using everything you learned
from the past.

00:47:44.560 --> 00:47:47.790
And your head should be like
a multimedia screen.

00:47:47.790 --> 00:47:53.370
Try to pick a lot of elements
and try to put those things

00:47:53.370 --> 00:47:55.000
inside of the music.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.220
Because the most important
thing is not the note.

00:47:57.220 --> 00:47:59.680
It's the things behind
the note, the

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:00.670
meaning behind the note.

00:48:00.670 --> 00:48:06.080
So the more meanings you're
getting, it's better for the

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:08.790
first work session.

00:48:08.790 --> 00:48:11.450
And then later, you're
just trying to

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:13.990
balance the right ones.

00:48:13.990 --> 00:48:16.870
And you will know the right
ones when you are ready.

00:48:16.870 --> 00:48:18.140
In the beginning, you
don't really know.

00:48:18.140 --> 00:48:19.600
So you try a lot of things.

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.020
And then later you will know,
wow, this will not work.

00:48:22.020 --> 00:48:26.110
Because this maybe doesn't
fit in the style.

00:48:26.110 --> 00:48:29.880
And then later, after you really
understand the dynamics

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:34.920
of the score, you start
to recreate things.

00:48:34.920 --> 00:48:40.030
And then you play for several
of your teachers or your

00:48:40.030 --> 00:48:43.270
colleagues to get more ideas.

00:48:43.270 --> 00:48:46.680
And then you start looking
into this work again.

00:48:46.680 --> 00:48:48.200
And then you start
performance.

00:48:48.200 --> 00:48:51.350
And when you perform, every day,
every time, you should

00:48:51.350 --> 00:48:52.880
try different things.

00:48:52.880 --> 00:48:55.600
And after a year, I think, you
are ready for recording.

00:48:58.240 --> 00:48:58.540
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:58.540 --> 00:49:01.260
LANG LANG: Lot of
alternatives.

00:49:01.260 --> 00:49:02.640
AUDIENCE: Hi, my
name is Zettai.

00:49:02.640 --> 00:49:04.070
I work in Google.

00:49:04.070 --> 00:49:07.690
And I actually have the opposite
problem from Samir

00:49:07.690 --> 00:49:10.090
with my two-and-a-half
year-old daughter.

00:49:10.090 --> 00:49:12.320
She actually loves
classical music.

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:12.610
LANG LANG: Yay!

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:14.080
Here we go, yeah.

00:49:14.080 --> 00:49:16.520
AUDIENCE: She even goes to sleep
while hearing Andrea

00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:20.120
Bocelli and you playing there,
which is very nice.

00:49:20.120 --> 00:49:22.560
And I have a different
question.

00:49:22.560 --> 00:49:26.160
I want to learn playing the
piano myself as well.

00:49:26.160 --> 00:49:27.460
LANG LANG: Wonderful.

00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:27.890
Wonderful.

00:49:27.890 --> 00:49:29.910
That's a great idea, yeah.

00:49:29.910 --> 00:49:30.645
AUDIENCE: I'm pretty
old, you know.

00:49:30.645 --> 00:49:32.620
I'm 35.

00:49:32.620 --> 00:49:35.700
And my question is actually
two part.

00:49:35.700 --> 00:49:37.100
First of all, I heard
about something

00:49:37.100 --> 00:49:39.960
called the Suzuki method.

00:49:39.960 --> 00:49:43.100
But I heard conflicting
opinions about it.

00:49:43.100 --> 00:49:45.310
So I wonder what's
your take on it.

00:49:45.310 --> 00:49:49.440
And the second part, is it--

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:50.650
how do you say it?

00:49:50.650 --> 00:49:55.850
Real ambition to learn to play
the piano at such a late age?

00:49:55.850 --> 00:49:59.091
And to do even something
minimum?

00:49:59.091 --> 00:50:00.940
LANG LANG: It's never
too late.

00:50:04.390 --> 00:50:08.550
Suzuki method, actually, I
didn't know that method when I

00:50:08.550 --> 00:50:10.040
was practicing.

00:50:10.040 --> 00:50:12.140
And then later, I
know the method.

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:17.320
But I've been brought up
by just playing scales.

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:21.520
So I didn't really
have any method.

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:23.050
Try this method or not.

00:50:23.050 --> 00:50:25.860
I think that maybe it's
important for some people.

00:50:25.860 --> 00:50:29.430
But it's not necessary to be
focused on one method.

00:50:29.430 --> 00:50:32.250
Because in the end of the day,
there's so many ways of

00:50:32.250 --> 00:50:33.460
playing piano.

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:37.470
And you don't want to start
with one thing in the very

00:50:37.470 --> 00:50:39.765
beginning, and you're
just stuck with it.

00:50:39.765 --> 00:50:43.080
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but I understood
the Suzuki method,

00:50:43.080 --> 00:50:47.170
both the father and the child
are learning together.

00:50:47.170 --> 00:50:48.890
I thought that's what--

00:50:48.890 --> 00:50:49.980
LANG LANG: My father
also did that.

00:50:49.980 --> 00:50:53.720
But it was a different
kind of method.

00:50:53.720 --> 00:50:58.158
He's playing, like,
the strict method.

00:50:58.158 --> 00:50:59.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:59.430 --> 00:51:01.680
LANG LANG: It doesn't matter.

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:04.850
But I'm sure it will work
for many people.

00:51:04.850 --> 00:51:08.760
I just didn't brought
up by that method.

00:51:08.760 --> 00:51:16.480
But this is a very challenging
way to know what is the real,

00:51:16.480 --> 00:51:22.160
right beginning method for
kids to learn piano?

00:51:22.160 --> 00:51:23.640
We'll still trying to
figure that out.

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:27.810
So once I know more about
it, I let you know.

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:31.120
But seriously, you can always
learn piano, no

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:32.640
matter how old you are.

00:51:32.640 --> 00:51:34.325
I have a doctor friend.

00:51:36.930 --> 00:51:39.370
He's a wonderful doctor,
lives in Germany.

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:43.320
And he's now, I think,
50 years old.

00:51:43.320 --> 00:51:44.610
JEFF SPURGEON: Good god, 50.

00:51:44.610 --> 00:51:46.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:46.510 --> 00:51:47.760
LANG LANG: Because he always
loved the piano.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:51.766
But he never had money to learn
when he was very young.

00:51:51.766 --> 00:51:54.170
He was focusing on medicine,
you know.

00:51:54.170 --> 00:51:58.790
Then somehow, after he became
a very successful doctor, he

00:51:58.790 --> 00:52:03.740
wanted to establish his
childhood dream, which is to

00:52:03.740 --> 00:52:06.410
play beautiful songs.

00:52:06.410 --> 00:52:13.100
And so he started to learn
piano when he turned 42.

00:52:13.100 --> 00:52:14.980
Seriously.

00:52:14.980 --> 00:52:18.920
And he found a teacher who was
very young, like, early 20s,

00:52:18.920 --> 00:52:23.770
but a very good guy, and
a very solid pianist.

00:52:23.770 --> 00:52:25.870
So he started learning
from him.

00:52:25.870 --> 00:52:28.080
And you what?

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:32.240
This 50-year-old doctor just
made his family archive

00:52:32.240 --> 00:52:36.800
recording of 10 of his favorite
pieces, including the

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:40.740
Schumann Traumerei, "Dreaming,"
including the

00:52:40.740 --> 00:52:45.300
Schubert Impromptus, including
Chopin's Waltz, including

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:47.140
Liszt Consolation.

00:52:47.140 --> 00:52:50.680
So this guy's only learned a
few years, but he has his

00:52:50.680 --> 00:52:53.070
golden Top 10.

00:52:53.070 --> 00:52:56.440
So he can open a radio show,
you know, Top 10.

00:52:56.440 --> 00:52:57.750
And he plays very beautiful.

00:52:57.750 --> 00:53:00.420
I mean, the technique maybe
is not really there.

00:53:00.420 --> 00:53:04.340
But he's certainly put his
emotions there, which is more

00:53:04.340 --> 00:53:05.840
important, somehow.

00:53:05.840 --> 00:53:07.330
And so I'm sure you
can do the same.

00:53:07.330 --> 00:53:09.110
And I'm sure you're much
younger than he is.

00:53:12.170 --> 00:53:13.120
JEFF SPURGEON: One
more question.

00:53:13.120 --> 00:53:14.470
You.

00:53:14.470 --> 00:53:17.730
AUDIENCE: So given the level
of evocativeness that you

00:53:17.730 --> 00:53:20.920
achieve, I have to wonder,
do you have some sort of

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:24.460
meditative practice other
than at the piano?

00:53:24.460 --> 00:53:28.020
What are your favorite ways to
tap into, say, greater levels

00:53:28.020 --> 00:53:29.270
of humanity?

00:53:34.380 --> 00:53:39.070
LANG LANG: I mean, the first
really important thing is

00:53:39.070 --> 00:53:40.200
taking naps.

00:53:40.200 --> 00:53:41.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:41.680 --> 00:53:42.860
LANG LANG: You're talking
about meditation, right.

00:53:42.860 --> 00:53:48.450
I mean, that's the first thing
that come to my mind.

00:53:48.450 --> 00:53:50.550
Because I'm such a night
person, I don't

00:53:50.550 --> 00:53:52.180
sleep well in the night.

00:53:52.180 --> 00:53:58.580
I just get over in my mind
with some strange ideas.

00:53:58.580 --> 00:54:01.230
But during the day, I like to
take a one-hour nap, and then

00:54:01.230 --> 00:54:05.110
somehow that calms me down,
and I feel great.

00:54:05.110 --> 00:54:13.570
And also, I think the best way
for ourselves to get ready

00:54:13.570 --> 00:54:16.130
mentally is reading books.

